# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: voltage-regulators-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] A **boost converter** or **step-up converter** is a DC-to-DC converter that increases voltage, while decreasing current, from its input (*supply*) to its output (*load*).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] It is a class of switched-mode power supply (SMPS) containing at least two semiconductors, a diode and a transistor, and at least one energy storage element: a capacitor, inductor, or the two in combination.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] To reduce voltage ripple, filters made of capacitors (sometimes in combination with inductors) are normally added to such a converter's output (load-side filter) and input (supply-side filter).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] Power for the boost converter can come from any suitable DC source, such as batteries, solar panels, rectifiers, and DC generators.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] A process that changes one DC voltage to a different DC voltage is called DC-to-DC conversion.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] A boost converter is a DC-to-DC converter with an output voltage greater than the source voltage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] A boost converter is sometimes called a step-up converter since it "steps up" the source voltage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] Since power ( ${\textstyle P=U\cdot I}$ ) must be conserved, the output current is lower than the source current.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] The hydraulic ram can be seen as the hydraulic analogue to a boost converter.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] For high efficiency, the switched-mode power supply (SMPS) switch must turn on and off quickly and have low losses.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] The advent of a commercial semiconductor switch in the 1950s represented a major milestone that made SMPSs such as the boost converter possible.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] The major DC-to-DC converters were developed in the early 1960s when semiconductor switches had become available.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] The aerospace industry’s need for small, lightweight, and efficient power converters led to the converter’s rapid development.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] Switched systems such as SMPS are a challenge to design since their models depend on whether a switch is opened or closed.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] Middlebrook from Caltech in 1977 published the models for DC-to-DC converters used today.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] Middlebrook averaged the circuit configurations for each switch state in a technique called state-space averaging.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] This simplification reduced two systems into one.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] The new model led to insightful design equations which helped the growth of SMPS.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] Battery power systems often stack cells in series to achieve higher voltage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] However, sufficient stacking of cells is not possible in many high voltage applications due to lack of space.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] Boost converters can increase the voltage and reduce the number of cells.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] Two battery-powered applications that use boost converters are used in hybrid electric vehicles (HEV) and lighting systems.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] The NHW20 model Toyota Prius HEV uses a 500 V motor.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] Without a boost converter, the Prius would need nearly 417 cells to power the motor.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] However, a Prius actually uses only 168 cells and boosts the battery voltage from 202 V to 500 V.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] Boost converters also power devices at smaller scale applications, such as portable lighting systems.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] A white LED typically requires 3.3 V to emit light, and a boost converter can step up the voltage from a single 1.5 V alkaline cell to power the lamp.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] An unregulated boost converter is used as the voltage increase mechanism in the circuit known as the "Joule thief", based on blocking oscillator concepts.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] This circuit topology is used with low power battery applications, and is aimed at the ability of a boost converter to "steal" the remaining energy in a battery.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] This energy would otherwise be wasted since the low voltage of a nearly depleted battery makes it unusable for a normal load.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] This voltage decrease occurs as batteries become depleted, and is a characteristic of the ubiquitous alkaline battery.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] Since the equation for power is ⁠ $\textstyle P={\frac {V^{2}}{R}}$ ⁠, and ⁠ R ⁠ tends to be stable, power available to the load goes down significantly as voltage decreases.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] The special kind of boost-converters called voltage-lift type boost converters are used in solar photovoltaic (PV) systems.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] These power converters add up the passive components (diode, inductor and capacitor) of a traditional boost-converter to improve the power quality and increase the performance of complete PV system.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] The key principle that drives the boost converter is the tendency of an inductor to resist changes in current by either increasing or decreasing the energy stored in the inductor's magnetic field.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] In a boost converter, the output voltage is always higher than the input voltage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] A schematic of a boost power stage is shown in Figure 1.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] When the switch is closed ('on-state'), current flows through the inductor in the clockwise direction and the inductor stores some energy by generating a magnetic field.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] The polarity of the left side of the inductor is positive.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] When the switch is opened ('off-state'), the magnetic field previously created will be reduced in energy to maintain the current through the inductor.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] The polarity of the inductor will be reversed, which means the left side of the inductor will become negative.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] If the switch is cycled fast enough, the inductor will not discharge fully in between charging stages, and the load will always see a voltage greater than that of the input source alone when the switch is opened.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] Also, while the switch is opened, the capacitor, in parallel with the load, is charged to this combined voltage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] When the switch is then closed, and the right-hand side is shorted out from the left-hand side, the capacitor is, therefore, able to provide the voltage and energy to the load.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] During this time, the blocking diode prevents the capacitor from discharging through the switch.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] The switch must, of course, be opened again fast enough to prevent the capacitor from discharging too much.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] This results in transferring the energy accumulated during the on-state into the capacitor.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] The input current is the same as the inductor current, as shown in Figure 2.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] So, it is not discontinuous as in the buck converter, and the requirements on the input filter are relaxed compared to a buck converter.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] When a boost converter operates in continuous mode, the current through the inductor, ⁠ $I_{\mathrm {L} }$ ⁠, never falls to zero.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] Figure 3 shows the typical waveforms of inductor current and voltage in a converter operating in this mode.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] In the steady state, the DC (average) voltage across the inductor must be zero so that after each cycle, the inductor returns the same state because the voltage across the inductor is proportional to the rate of change of current through it (explained in more detail below).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] Note in Figure 1 that the left-hand side of ⁠ L ⁠ is at ⁠ $V_{\mathrm {i} }$ ⁠, and the right-hand side of ⁠ L ⁠ sees the $V_{\mathrm {S} }$ voltage waveform from Figure 3.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] The average value of $V_{\mathrm {S} }$ is ⁠ $(1-D)V_{\mathrm {o} }$ ⁠, where ⁠ D ⁠ is the duty cycle of the waveform driving the switch.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] It represents the fraction of the commutation period T during which the switch is on.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] Therefore, D ranges between 0 (S is never on) and 1 (S is always on).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] During the off-state, the switch S is open, so the inductor current flows through the load.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] As we consider that the converter operates in steady state conditions, the amount of energy stored in each of its components has to be the same at the beginning and at the end of a commutation cycle.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] So, the inductor current has to be the same at the start and end of the commutation cycle.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] The above equation shows that the output voltage is always higher than the input voltage (as the duty cycle goes from 0 to 1), and that it increases with ⁠ D ⁠, theoretically to infinity as D approaches 1.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] This is why this converter is sometimes referred to as a 'step-up' converter.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] If the ripple amplitude of the current is too high, the inductor may be completely discharged before the end of a whole commutation cycle.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] In this case, the current through the inductor falls to zero during part of the period (see waveforms in Figure 4).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] Although the difference is slight, it has a strong effect on the output voltage equation.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] The load current $I_{\mathrm {o} }$ is equal to the average diode current ⁠ $I_{\mathrm {D} }$ ⁠.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] As can be seen in Figure 4, the diode current is equal to the inductor current during the off-state.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] The average value of $I_{\mathrm {o} }$ can be sorted out geometrically from Figure 4.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] Compared to the expression of the output voltage gain for continuous mode, this expression is much more complicated.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/boost-converter] Furthermore, in discontinuous operation, the output voltage gain not only depends on the duty cycle ⁠ D ⁠, but also on the inductor value ⁠ L ⁠, the input voltage ⁠ $V_{\mathrm {i} }$ ⁠, the commutation period ⁠ T ⁠, and the output current ⁠ $I_{\mathrm {o} }$ ⁠.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] A **buck converter** or **step-down converter** is a DC-to-DC converter which decreases voltage, while increasing current, from its input (*supply*) to its output (*load*).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] It is a class of switched-mode power supply.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Switching converters (such as buck converters) provide much greater power efficiency as DC-to-DC converters than linear regulators, which are simpler circuits that dissipate power as heat, but do not step up output current.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] The efficiency of buck converters can be very high, often over 90%, making them useful for tasks such as converting a computer's main supply voltage, which is usually 12 V, down to lower voltages needed by USB, DRAM and the CPU, which are usually 5, 3.3 or 1.8 V.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] To reduce voltage ripple, filters made of capacitors (sometimes in combination with additional inductors) are normally added to such a converter's output (load-side filter) and input (supply-side filter).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Its name derives from the inductor that “bucks” or opposes the supply voltage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Buck converters typically operate with a switching frequency range from 100 kHz to a few MHz.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] A higher switching frequency allows for use of smaller inductors and capacitors, but also increases lost efficiency to more frequent transistor switching.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Disconnect the source and use the inertia of the current in the inductor to provide more current than the source delivers ("off" in fig.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] To close the circuit with the source disconnected, a second switch, usually a diode, is needed.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] During on-state, the source may need to momentarily provide more current than its rating for constant load allows, but the on-time is too short for the source to take damage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] During off-state, no current is drawn from the source, and the components can cool down.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] The average current draw over both states needs to be below the source specification.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] To even out voltage spikes from the switching between on-state and off-state, a capacitor is used on the output side.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] A mechanical analogy for a buck converter would be to pedal a bicycle in single, strong bursts (force ~ voltage), and let the bicycle roll in between (inertia ~ inductor).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] The basic operation of the buck converter has the current in an inductor controlled by two switches (fig.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] In a physical implementation, these switches are realized by a transistor and a diode, or two transistors (which avoids the loss associated with the diode's voltage drop).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] The conceptual model of the buck converter is best understood in terms of the relation between current and voltage of the inductor.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Beginning with the switch open (off-state), the current in the circuit is zero.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] When the switch is first closed (on-state), the current will begin to increase, and the inductor will produce an opposing voltage across its terminals in response to the changing current.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] This voltage drop counteracts the voltage of the source and therefore reduces the net voltage across the load.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Over time, the rate of change of current decreases, and the voltage across the inductor also then decreases, increasing the voltage at the load.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] During this time, the inductor stores energy in the form of a magnetic field.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] If the switch is opened while the current is still changing, then there will always be a voltage drop across the inductor, so the net voltage at the load will always be less than the input voltage source.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] When the switch is opened again (off-state), the voltage source will be removed from the circuit, and the current will decrease.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] The decreasing current will produce a voltage drop across the inductor (opposite to the drop at on-state), and now the inductor becomes a current source.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] The stored energy in the inductor's magnetic field supports the current flow through the load.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] This current, flowing while the input voltage source is disconnected, when appended to the current flowing during on-state, totals to current greater than the average input current (being zero during off-state).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] The increase in average current makes up for the reduction in voltage, and ideally preserves the power provided to the load.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] During the off-state, the inductor is discharging its stored energy into the rest of the circuit.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] If the switch is closed again before the inductor fully discharges (on-state), the voltage at the load will always be greater than zero.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Buck converters operate in continuous mode if the current through the inductor ( $I_{\text{L}}$ ) never falls to zero during the commutation cycle.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Therefore, it can be seen that the energy stored in L increases during on-time as $I_{\text{L}}$ increases and then decreases during the off-state.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] L is used to transfer energy from the input to the output of the converter.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] where D is a scalar called the duty cycle with a value between 0 and 1.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Assuming that the converter operates in the steady state, the energy stored in each component at the end of a commutation cycle T is equal to that at the beginning of the cycle.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] That means that the current $I_{\text{L}}$ is the same at $t=0$ and at $t=T$ (figure 4).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] The above integrations can be done graphically.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] In figure 4, $\Delta I_{L_{\text{on}}}$ is proportional to the area of the yellow surface, and $\Delta I_{L_{\text{off}}}$ to the area of the orange surface, as these surfaces are defined by the inductor voltage (red lines).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] As these surfaces are simple rectangles, their areas can be found easily: $\left(V_{\text{i}}-V_{\text{o}}\right)t_{\text{on}}$ for the yellow rectangle and $-V_{\text{o}}t_{\text{off}}$ for the orange one.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] For steady state operation, these areas must be equal.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] From this equation, it can be seen that the output voltage of the converter varies linearly with the duty cycle for a given input voltage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] As the duty cycle D is equal to the ratio between $t_{\text{on}}$ and the period T , it cannot be more than 1.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] This is why this converter is referred to as *step-down converter*.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] So, for example, stepping 12 V down to 3 V (output voltage equal to one quarter of the input voltage) would require a duty cycle of 25%, in this theoretically ideal circuit.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] In some cases, the amount of energy required by the load is too small.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] In this case, the current through the inductor falls to zero during part of the period.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] The only difference in the principle described above is that the inductor is completely discharged at the end of the commutation cycle (see figure 5).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] This has, however, some effect on the previous equations.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] The inductor current falling below zero results in the discharging of the output capacitor during each cycle and therefore higher switching losses.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] A different control technique known as pulse-frequency modulation can be used to minimize these losses.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] We still consider that the converter operates in steady state.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Therefore, the energy in the inductor is the same at the beginning and at the end of the cycle (in the case of discontinuous mode, it is zero).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] This means that the average value of the inductor voltage (VL) is zero; i.e., that the area of the yellow and orange rectangles in figure 5 are the same.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] The output current delivered to the load ( $I_{\text{o}}$ ) is constant, as we consider that the output capacitor is large enough to maintain a constant voltage across its terminals during a commutation cycle.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] This implies that the current flowing through the capacitor has a zero average value.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Where ${\overline {I_{\text{L}}}}$ is the average value of the inductor current.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] As can be seen in figure 5, the inductor current waveform has a triangular shape.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] The inductor current is zero at the beginning and rises during ton up to ILmax.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] It can be seen that the output voltage of a buck converter operating in discontinuous mode is much more complicated than its counterpart of the continuous mode.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Furthermore, the output voltage is now a function not only of the input voltage (Vi) and the duty cycle D, but also of the inductor value (L), the commutation period (T) and the output current (Io).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] The converter operates in discontinuous mode when low current is drawn by the load, and in continuous mode at higher load current levels.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] The limit between discontinuous and continuous modes is reached when the inductor current falls to zero exactly at the end of the commutation cycle.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] On the limit between the two modes, the output voltage obeys both the expressions given respectively in the continuous and the discontinuous sections.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] These expressions have been plotted in figure 6.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] From this, it can be deduced that in continuous mode, the output voltage does only depend on the duty cycle, whereas it is far more complex in the discontinuous mode.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] This is important from a control point of view.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] These assumptions can be fairly far from reality, and the imperfections of the real components can have a detrimental effect on the operation of the converter.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Output voltage ripple is the name given to the phenomenon where the output voltage rises during the On-state and falls during the Off-state.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Several factors contribute to this including, but not limited to, switching frequency, output capacitance, inductor, load and any current limiting features of the control circuitry.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] We can best approximate output ripple voltage by shifting the output current versus time waveform (continuous mode) down so that the average output current is along the time axis.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] When we do this, we see the AC current waveform flowing into and out of the output capacitor (sawtooth waveform).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] We note that *V*c-min (where *V*c is the capacitor voltage) occurs at *t*on/2 (just after capacitor has discharged) and *V*c-max at *t*off/2.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] A full explanation is given there.) We note from basic AC circuit theory that our ripple voltage should be roughly sinusoidal: capacitor impedance times ripple current peak-to-peak value, or Δ*V* = Δ*I* / (ω*C*) where ω = 2π*f*, *f* is the ripple frequency, and *f* = 1/*T*, *T* the ripple period.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] This gives: Δ*V* = Δ*I* *T*/2π*C*), and we compare to this value to confirm the above in that we have a factor of 8 vs a factor of ~ 6.3 from basic AC circuit theory for a sinusoid.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] This gives confidence in our assessment here of ripple voltage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] The paragraph directly below pertains that directly above and may be incorrect.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Once again, please see talk tab for more: pertaining output ripple voltage and AoE (Art of Electronics 3rd edition).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] During the off-state, the current in this equation is the load current.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] In the on-state the current is the difference between the switch current (or source current) and the load current.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] The duration of time (d*T*) is defined by the duty cycle and by the switching frequency.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Qualitatively, as the output capacitance or switching frequency increase, the magnitude of the ripple decreases.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Output voltage ripple is typically a design specification for the power supply and is selected based on several factors.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Capacitor selection is normally determined based on cost, physical size and non-idealities of various capacitor types.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Switching frequency selection is typically determined based on efficiency requirements, which tends to decrease at higher operating frequencies, as described below in Effects of non-ideality on the efficiency.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Higher switching frequency can also raise EMI concerns.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Output voltage ripple is one of the disadvantages of a switching power supply, and can also be a measure of its quality.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] The simplified analysis above, does not account for non-idealities of the circuit components nor does it account for the required control circuitry.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Power losses due to the control circuitry are usually insignificant when compared with the losses in the power devices (switches, diodes, inductors, etc.) The non-idealities of the power devices account for the bulk of the power losses in the converter.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Both static and dynamic power losses occur in any switching regulator.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Static power losses include $I^{2}R$ (conduction) losses in the wires or PCB traces, as well as in the switches and inductor, as in any electrical circuit.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Dynamic power losses occur as a result of switching, such as the charging and discharging of the switch gate, and are proportional to the switching frequency.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] The voltage drops described above are all static power losses which are dependent primarily on DC current, and can therefore be easily calculated.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] For a diode drop, *V*sw and *V*sw,sync may already be known, based on the properties of the selected device.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] The duty cycle equation is somewhat recursive.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] A rough analysis can be made by first calculating the values *V*sw and *V*sw,sync using the ideal duty cycle equation.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] For a MOSFET voltage drop, a common approximation is to use RDSon from the MOSFET's datasheet in Ohm's law, V = IDSRDSon(sat).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] This approximation is acceptable because the MOSFET is in the linear state, with a relatively constant drain-source resistance.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] This approximation is only valid at relatively low VDS values.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] For more accurate calculations, MOSFET datasheets contain graphs on the VDS and IDS relationship at multiple VGS values.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Observe VDS at the VGS and IDS which most closely match what is expected in the buck converter.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] In addition, power loss occurs as a result of leakage currents.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Dynamic power losses are due to the switching behavior of the selected pass devices (MOSFETs, power transistors, IGBTs, etc.).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] These losses include turn-on and turn-off switching losses and switch transition losses.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] but this does not take into account the parasitic capacitance of the MOSFET which makes the *Miller plate*.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] When a MOSFET is used for the lower switch, additional losses may occur during the time between the turn-off of the high-side switch and the turn-on of the low-side switch, when the body diode of the low-side MOSFET conducts the output current.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] This time, known as the non-overlap time, prevents "shoot-through", a condition in which both switches are simultaneously turned on.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] The onset of shoot-through generates severe power loss and heat.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Proper selection of non-overlap time must balance the risk of shoot-through with the increased power loss caused by conduction of the body diode.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Many MOSFET based buck converters also include a diode to aid the lower MOSFET body diode with conduction during the non-overlap time.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] When a diode is used exclusively for the lower switch, diode forward turn-on time can reduce efficiency and lead to voltage overshoot.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Finally, power losses occur as a result of the power required to turn the switches on and off.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] For MOSFET switches, these losses are dominated by the energy required to charge and discharge the capacitance of the MOSFET gate between the threshold voltage and the selected gate voltage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] These switch transition losses occur primarily in the gate driver, and can be minimized by selecting MOSFETs with low gate charge, by driving the MOSFET gate to a lower voltage (at the cost of increased MOSFET conduction losses), or by operating at a lower frequency.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] For N-MOSFETs, the high-side switch must be driven to a higher voltage than *Vi*.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] To achieve this, MOSFET gate drivers typically feed the MOSFET output voltage back into the gate driver.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] The gate driver then adds its own supply voltage to the MOSFET output voltage when driving the high-side MOSFETs to achieve a *VGS* equal to the gate driver supply voltage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Because the low-side *VGS* is the gate driver supply voltage, this results in very similar *VGS* values for high-side and low-side MOSFETs.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] A complete design for a buck converter includes a tradeoff analysis of the various power losses.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Designers balance these losses according to the expected uses of the finished design.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] A converter expected to have a low switching frequency does not require switches with low gate transition losses; a converter operating at a high duty cycle requires a low-side switch with low conduction losses.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] A synchronous buck converter is a modified version of the basic buck converter circuit topology in which the diode, D, is replaced by a second switch, S2.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] This modification is a tradeoff between increased cost and improved efficiency.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] In a standard buck converter, the flyback diode turns on, on its own, shortly after the switch turns off, as a result of the rising voltage across the diode.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] By replacing the diode with a switch selected for low loss, the converter efficiency can be improved.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] In both cases, power loss is strongly dependent on the duty cycle, D.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Power loss on the freewheeling diode or lower switch will be proportional to its on-time.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Therefore, systems designed for low duty cycle operation will suffer from higher losses in the freewheeling diode or lower switch, and for such systems it is advantageous to consider a synchronous buck converter design.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Consider a computer power supply, where the input is 5 V, the output is 3.3 V, and the load current is 10 A.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] In this case, the duty cycle will be 66% and the diode would be on for 34% of the time.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] A typical diode with forward voltage of 0.7 V would suffer a power loss of 2.38 W.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] A well-selected MOSFET with RDSon of 0.015 Ω, however, would waste only 0.51 W in conduction loss.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] This translates to improved efficiency and reduced heat generation.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Another advantage of the synchronous converter is that it is bi-directional, which lends itself to applications requiring regenerative braking.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] When power is transferred in the "reverse" direction, it acts much like a boost converter.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] The advantages of the synchronous buck converter do not come without cost.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] First, the lower switch typically costs more than the freewheeling diode.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Second, the complexity of the converter is vastly increased due to the need for a complementary-output switch driver.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Such a driver must prevent both switches from being turned on at the same time, a fault known as "shootthrough".
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] The simplest technique for avoiding shootthrough is a time delay between the turn-off of S1 to the turn-on of S2, and vice versa.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] However, setting this time delay long enough to ensure that S1 and S2 are never both on will itself result in excess power loss.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] An improved technique for preventing this condition is known as adaptive "non-overlap" protection, in which the voltage at the switch node (the point where S1, S2 and L are joined) is sensed to determine its state.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] When the switch node voltage passes a preset threshold, the time delay is started.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] The driver can thus adjust to many types of switches without the excessive power loss this flexibility would cause with a fixed non-overlap time.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Both low side and high side switches may be turned off in response to a load transient and the body diode in the low side MOSFET or another diode in parallel with it becomes active.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] The higher voltage drop on the low side switch is then of benefit, helping to reduce current output and meet the new load requirement sooner.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] The multiphase buck converter is a circuit topology where basic buck converter circuits are placed in parallel between the input and load.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Each of the *n* "phases" is turned on at equally spaced intervals over the switching period.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] This circuit is typically used with the synchronous buck topology, described above.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] This type of converter can respond to load changes as quickly as if it switched *n* times faster, without the increase in switching losses that would cause.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Thus, it can respond to rapidly changing loads, such as modern microprocessors.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] There is also a significant decrease in switching ripple.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Another advantage is that the load current is split among the *n* phases of the multiphase converter.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] This load splitting allows the heat losses on each of the switches to be spread across a larger area.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] This circuit topology is used in computer motherboards to convert the 12 VDC power supply to a lower voltage (around 1 V), suitable for the CPU.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Modern CPU power requirements can exceed 200 W, can change very rapidly, and have very tight ripple requirements, less than 10 mV.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Typical CPU power supplies found on mainstream motherboards use 3 or 4 phases, while high-end systems can have 16 or more phases.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] One major challenge inherent in the multiphase converter is ensuring the load current is balanced evenly across the *n* phases.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] This current balancing can be performed in a number of ways.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Current can be measured "losslessly" by sensing the voltage across the inductor or the lower switch (when it is turned on).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] This technique is considered lossless because it relies on resistive losses inherent in the buck converter topology.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Another technique is to insert a small resistor in the circuit and measure the voltage across it.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] This approach is more accurate and adjustable, but incurs several costs—space, efficiency and money.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Finally, the current can be measured at the input.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Voltage can be measured losslessly, across the upper switch, or using a power resistor, to approximate the current being drawn.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] This approach is technically more challenging, since switching noise cannot be easily filtered out.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] However, it is less expensive than having a sense resistor for each phase.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] There are two main phenomena impacting the efficiency: conduction losses and switching losses.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Conduction losses happen when current is flowing through the components and thus depend on the load.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] They are caused by Joule effect in the resistance when the transistor or MOSFET switch is conducting, the inductor winding resistance, and the capacitor equivalent series resistance.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Losses are proportional to the square of the current in this case.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Conduction losses are also generated by the diode forward voltage drop (usually 0.7 V or 0.4 V for Schottky diode), and are proportional to the current in this case.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] Switching losses happen in the transistor and diode when the voltage and the current overlap during the transitions between closed and open states.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] A Schottky diode can be used to minimize the switching losses caused by the reverse recovery of a regular PN diode.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] The switching losses are proportional to the switching frequency.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] In a complete real-world buck converter, there is also a command circuit to regulate the output voltage or the inductor current.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] This circuit and the MOSFET gate controller have a power consumption, impacting the overall efficiency of the converter.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] A buck converter can be used to maximize the power transfer through the use of impedance matching.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] An application of this is in a *maximum power point tracker* commonly used in photovoltaic systems.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/buck-converter] This is particularly useful in applications where the impedances are dynamically changing.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] A **DC-to-DC converter** is an electronic circuit or electromechanical device that converts a source of direct current (DC) from one voltage level to another DC.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] It is a type of electric power converter.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] Power levels range from very low (small batteries) to very high (high-voltage power transmission).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] Before the development of power semiconductors, one way to convert the voltage of a DC supply to a higher voltage, for low-power applications, was to convert it to AC by using a vibrator, then by a step-up transformer, and finally a rectifier.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] Where higher power was needed, a motor–generator unit was often used, in which an electric motor drove a generator that produced the desired voltage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] The introduction of power semiconductors and integrated circuits made it economically viable by use of techniques described below.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] For example, first is converting the DC power supply to high-frequency AC as an input of a transformer - it is small, light, and cheap due to the high frequency — that changes the voltage which gets rectified back to DC.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] Although by 1976 transistor car radio receivers did not require high voltages, some amateur radio operators continued to use vibrator supplies and dynamotors for mobile transceivers requiring high voltages even though transistorized power supplies were available.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] While it was possible to derive a *lower* voltage from a higher with a linear regulator or even a resistor, these methods dissipated the excess energy as heat; energy-efficient conversion became possible only with solid-state switch-mode circuits.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] DC-to-DC converters are used in portable electronic devices such as cellular phones and laptop computers, which are supplied with power from batteries primarily.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] Such electronic devices often contain several sub-circuits, each with its own voltage level requirement different from that supplied by the battery or an external supply (sometimes higher or lower than the supply voltage).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] Additionally, the battery voltage declines as its stored energy is drained.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] Switched DC to DC converters offer a method to increase voltage from a partially lowered battery voltage thereby saving space instead of using multiple batteries to accomplish the same thing.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] Most DC-to-DC converter circuits also regulate the output voltage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] Some exceptions include high-efficiency LED power sources, which are a kind of DC to DC converter that regulates the current through the LEDs, and simple charge pumps which double or triple the output voltage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] DC-to-DC converters which are designed to maximize the energy harvest for photovoltaic systems and for wind turbines are called power optimizers.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] In electric vehicles, DC-DC converters step down the high voltage of the propulsion battery to 12 volts to allow use of accessories such as lighting, climate control fans, entertainment electronics, and other systems.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] This converter may also recharge the 12 volt auxiliary battery used for startup and standby loads such as keyless entry or security systems while the vehicle is idle.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] Most DC-to-DC converters are designed to move power in only one direction, from dedicated input to output.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] However, all switching regulator topologies can be made bidirectional and able to move power in either direction by replacing all diodes with independently controlled active rectification.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] A bidirectional converter is useful, for example, in applications requiring regenerative braking of vehicles, where power is supplied *to* the wheels while driving, but supplied *by* the wheels when braking.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] Although they require few components, switching converters are electronically complex.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] Like all high-frequency circuits, their components must be carefully specified and physically arranged to achieve stable operation and to keep switching noise (EMI / RFI) at acceptable levels.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] Their cost is higher than linear regulators in voltage-dropping applications, but their cost has been decreasing with advances in chip design.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] DC-to-DC converters are available as integrated circuits (ICs) requiring few additional components.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] Converters are also available as complete hybrid circuit modules, ready for use within an electronic assembly.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] Linear regulators which are used to output a stable DC independent of input voltage and output load from a higher but less stable input by dissipating excess volt-amperes as heat, could be described literally as DC-to-DC converters, but this is not usual usage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] There are also simple capacitive voltage doubler and Dickson multiplier circuits using diodes and capacitors to multiply a DC voltage by an integer value, typically delivering only a small current.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] In these DC-to-DC converters, energy is periodically stored within and released from a magnetic field in an inductor or a transformer, typically within a frequency range of 300 kHz to 10 MHz.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] By adjusting the duty cycle of the charging voltage (that is, the ratio of the on/off times), the amount of power transferred to a load can be more easily controlled, though this control can also be applied to the input current, the output current, or to maintain constant power.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] Transformer-based converters may provide isolation between input and output.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] In general, the term *DC-to-DC converter* refers to one of these switching converters.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] These circuits are the heart of a switched-mode power supply.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] A converter may be designed to operate in continuous mode at high power, and in discontinuous mode at low power.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] The half bridge and flyback topologies are similar in that energy stored in the magnetic core needs to be dissipated so that the core does not saturate.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] Power transmission in a flyback circuit is limited by the amount of energy that can be stored in the core, while forward circuits are usually limited by the I/V characteristics of the switches.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] Although MOSFET switches can tolerate simultaneous full current and voltage (although thermal stress and electromigration can shorten the MTBF), bipolar switches generally can't so require the use of a snubber (or two).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] High-current systems often use multiphase converters, also called interleaved converters.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] Multiphase regulators can have better ripple and better response times than single-phase regulators.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] Many laptop and desktop motherboards include interleaved buck regulators, sometimes as a voltage regulator module.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] Specific to these converters is that the energy flows in both directions of the converter.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] These converters are commonly used in various applications and they are connected between two levels of DC voltage, where energy is transferred from one level to another.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] Multiple isolated bidirectional DC-to-DC converters are also commonly used in cases where galvanic isolation is needed.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] Switched capacitor converters rely on alternately connecting capacitors to the input and output in differing topologies.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] For example, a switched-capacitor reducing converter might charge two capacitors in series and then discharge them in parallel.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] This would produce the same output power (less that lost to efficiency of under 100%) at, ideally, half the input voltage and twice the current.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] Because they operate on discrete quantities of charge, these are also sometimes referred to as charge pump converters.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] They are typically used in applications requiring relatively small currents, as at higher currents the increased efficiency and smaller size of switch-mode converters makes them a better choice.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] They are also used at extremely high voltages, as magnetics would break down at such voltages.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] Before the availability of power electronics devices, electromechanical converters were commercially important.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] A motor–generator set consists of an electric motor and generator coupled together.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] A *dynamotor* combines both functions into a single unit with coils for both the motor and the generator functions wound around a single rotor; both coils share the same outer field coils or magnets.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] Typically the motor coils are driven from a commutator on one end of the shaft, when the generator coils output to another commutator on the other end of the shaft.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] The entire rotor and shaft assembly is smaller in size than a pair of machines, and may not have any exposed drive shafts.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] Motor–generators can convert between any combination of DC and AC voltage and phase standards.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] Large motor–generator sets were widely used to convert industrial amounts of power while smaller units were used to convert battery power (6, 12 or 24 V DC) to a high DC voltage, which was required to operate vacuum tube (thermionic valve) equipment.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] For lower-power requirements at voltages higher than supplied by a vehicle battery, vibrator or "buzzer" power supplies were used.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] The vibrator oscillated mechanically, with contacts that switched the polarity of the battery many times per second, effectively converting DC to square wave AC, which could then be fed to a transformer of the required output voltage(s).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] Electronic converters eventually replaced electromechanical converters since they had no moving parts (aside from cooling fans), and were generally smaller, lighter, and eventually cheaper than electromechanical converters of similar rating.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] DC-to-DC converters are subject to different types of chaotic dynamics such as bifurcation, crisis, and intermittency.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] Current and thus the magnetic field in the inductive energy storage never reaches zero.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] Current and thus the magnetic field in the inductive energy storage may reach or cross zero.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] at the switching frequency and its harmonics.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] in continuous current mode, produce less harmonic noise than other switching converters.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] Acceptable levels depend upon requirements, e.g. proximity to RF circuitry needs more suppression than simply meeting regulations.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] These may include a power control IC, coil, capacitor, and resistor; decreases mounting space with a small number of components in a single integrated solution.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] The input voltage may have non-negligible noise.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] Additionally, if the converter loads the input with sharp load edges, the converter can emit RF noise from the supplying power lines.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] This should be prevented with proper filtering in the input stage of the converter.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] The output of an ideal DC-to-DC converter is a flat, constant output voltage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] However, real converters produce a DC output upon which is superimposed some level of electrical noise.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] Switching converters produce switching noise at the switching frequency and its harmonics.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] Some sensitive radio-frequency and analog circuits require a power supply with so little noise that it can only be provided by a linear regulator.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/dc-to-dc-converter] Some analog circuits which require a power supply with relatively low noise can tolerate some of the less-noisy switching converters, e.g. using continuous triangular waveforms rather than square waves.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] In electronics, a **linear regulator** is a voltage regulator used to maintain a steady voltage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] The resistance of the regulator varies in accordance with both the input voltage and the load, resulting in a constant voltage output.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] The regulating circuit varies its resistance, continuously adjusting a voltage divider network to maintain a constant output voltage and continually dissipating the difference between the input and regulated voltages as waste heat.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] By contrast, a *switching regulator* uses an active device that switches on and off to maintain an average value of output.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] Because the regulated voltage of a linear regulator must always be lower than input voltage, efficiency is limited and the input voltage must be high enough to always allow the active device to reduce the voltage by some amount.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] Linear regulators may place the regulating device in parallel with the load (shunt regulator) or may place the regulating device between the source and the regulated load (a series regulator).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] Simple linear regulators may only contain as little as a Zener diode and a series resistor; more complicated regulators include separate stages of voltage reference, error amplifier and power pass element.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] Because a linear voltage regulator is a common element of many devices, single-chip regulators ICs are very common.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] Linear regulators may also be made up of assemblies of discrete solid-state or vacuum tube components.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] The transistor (or other device) is used as one half of a voltage divider to establish the regulated output voltage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] The output voltage is compared to a reference voltage to produce a control signal to the transistor which will drive its gate or base.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] With negative feedback and good choice of compensation, the output voltage is kept reasonably constant.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] Linear regulators are often inefficient: since the transistor is acting like a resistor, it will waste electrical energy by converting it to heat.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] In fact, the power loss due to heating in the transistor is the current multiplied by the voltage difference between input and output voltage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] The same function can often be performed much more efficiently by a switched-mode power supply, but a linear regulator may be preferred for light loads or where the desired output voltage approaches the source voltage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] In these cases, the linear regulator may dissipate less power than a switcher.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] The linear regulator also has the advantage of not requiring magnetic devices (inductors or transformers) which can be relatively expensive or bulky, being often of simpler design, and cause less electromagnetic interference.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] Some designs of linear regulators use only transistors, diodes and resistors, which are easier to fabricate into an integrated circuit, further reducing their weight, footprint on a PCB, and price.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] All linear regulators require an input voltage at least some minimum amount higher than the desired output voltage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] That minimum amount is called the dropout voltage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] For example, a common regulator such as the 7805 has an output voltage of 5 V, but can only maintain this if the input voltage remains above about 7 V, before the output voltage begins sagging below the rated output.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] Its dropout voltage is therefore 7 V − 5 V = 2 V.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] When the supply voltage is less than about 2 V above the desired output voltage, as is the case in low-voltage microprocessor power supplies, so-called low dropout regulators (LDOs) must be used.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] When the output regulated voltage must be higher than the available input voltage, no linear regulator will work (not even a low dropout regulator).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] In this situation, a boost converter or a charge pump must be used.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] Most linear regulators will continue to provide some output voltage approximately the dropout voltage below the input voltage for inputs below the nominal output voltage until the input voltage drops significantly.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] Linear regulators exist in two basic forms: shunt regulators and series regulators.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] Most linear regulators have a maximum rated output current.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] This is generally limited by either power dissipation capability, or by the current carrying capability of the output transistor.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] The shunt regulator works by providing a path from the supply voltage to ground through a variable resistance (the main transistor is in the "bottom half" of the voltage divider).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] The current through the shunt regulator is diverted away from the load and flows directly to ground, making this form usually less efficient than the series regulator.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] It is, however, simpler, sometimes consisting of just a voltage-reference diode, and is used in very low-powered circuits where the wasted current is too small to be of concern.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] This form is very common for voltage reference circuits.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] A shunt regulator can usually only sink (absorb) current.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] The resistor *R*1 supplies the Zener current *I*Z as well as the load current *I*R2 (*R*2 is the load).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] This regulator is used for very simple low-power applications where the currents involved are very small and the load is permanently connected across the Zener diode (such as voltage reference or voltage source circuits).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] Once *R*1 has been calculated, removing *R*2 will allow the full load current (plus the Zener current) through the diode and may exceed the diode's maximum current rating, thereby damaging it.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] The regulation of this circuit is also not very good because the Zener current (and hence the Zener voltage) will vary depending on *V*S and inversely depending on the load current.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] In some designs, the Zener diode may be replaced with another similarly functioning device, especially in an ultra-low-voltage scenario, like (under forward bias) several normal diodes or LEDs in series.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] Series regulators are the more common form; they are more efficient than shunt designs.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] The series regulator works by providing a path from the supply voltage to the load through a variable resistance, usually a transistor (in this role it is usually termed the series **pass transistor**); it is in the "top half" of the voltage divider - the bottom half being the load.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] The power dissipated by the regulating device is equal to the power supply output current times the *voltage drop* in the regulating device.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] Here, the load current *I*R2 is supplied by the transistor whose base is now connected to the Zener diode.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] Thus the transistor's base current (*I*B) forms the load current for the Zener diode and is much smaller than the current through *R*2.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] This regulator is classified as "series" because the regulating element, viz., the transistor, appears in series with the load.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] This circuit has much better regulation than the simple shunt regulator, since the base current of the transistor forms a very light load on the Zener, shielding the Zener voltage from load variation.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] Note that the output voltage will always be about 0.65 V less than the Zener due to the transistor's *V*BE drop.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] Although this circuit has good regulation, it is still sensitive to load and supply variation.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] This can be resolved by incorporating negative feedback circuitry into it.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] This regulator is often used as a "pre-regulator" in more advanced series voltage regulator circuits.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] The circuit is readily made adjustable by adding a potentiometer across the Zener, moving the transistor base connection from the top of the Zener to the pot wiper.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] It may be made step adjustable by switching in different Zeners.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] Finally, it is occasionally made microadjustable by adding a low value pot in series with the Zener; this allows a little voltage adjustment, but degrades regulation (see also capacitance multiplier).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] Three-terminal linear regulators, used for generating "fixed" voltages, are readily available.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] They can generate plus or minus 3.3 V, 5 V, 6 V, 9 V, 12 V, or 15 V, with their performance generally peaking around a load of 1.5 Amperes.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] The "78xx" series (7805, 7812, etc.) regulate positive voltages while the "79xx" series (7905, 7912, etc.) regulate negative voltages.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] Often, the last two digits of the device number are the output voltage (e.g., a 7805 is a +5 V regulator, while a 7915 is a −15 V regulator).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] There are variants on the 78xx series ICs, such as 78L and 78S, some of which can supply up to 2 A.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] By adding another circuit element to a fixed voltage IC regulator, it is possible to adjust the output voltage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] A potentiometer can be placed in series with the ground terminal to increase the output voltage variably.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] However, this method degrades regulation, and is not suitable for regulators with varying ground current.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] An adjustable regulator generates a fixed low nominal voltage between its output and its adjust terminal (equivalent to the ground terminal in a fixed regulator).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] This family of devices includes low power devices like **LM723** and medium power devices like **LM317** and **L200**.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] Some of the variable regulators are available in packages with more than three pins, including dual in-line packages.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] They offer the capability to adjust the output voltage by using external resistors of specific values.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] For output voltages not provided by standard fixed regulators and load currents of less than 7 A, commonly available adjustable three-terminal linear regulators may be used.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] The **LM317** series (+1.25 V) regulates positive voltages while the **LM337** series (−1.25 V) regulates negative voltages.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] The adjustment is performed by constructing a potential divider with its ends between the regulator output and ground, and its centre-tap connected to the 'adjust' terminal of the regulator.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] The ratio of resistances determines the output voltage using the same feedback mechanisms described earlier.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] Single IC dual tracking adjustable regulators are available for applications such as op-amp circuits needing matched positive and negative DC supplies.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] Some have selectable current limiting as well.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] One example of a single IC dual tracking adjustable regulator is the **LM125**, which is a precision, dual, tracking, monolithic voltage regulator.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] It provides separate positive and negative regulated outputs, simplifying dual power supply designs.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] Operation requires few or no external components, depending on the application.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] Sometimes external protection is used, such as crowbar protection.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] Linear regulators can be constructed using discrete components but are usually encountered in integrated circuit forms.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] The most common linear regulators are three-terminal integrated circuits in the TO-220 package.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] Common voltage regulators are the LM78xx-series (for positive voltages) and LM79xx-series (for negative voltages).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] Robust automotive voltage regulators, such as LM2940 / MIC2940A / AZ2940, can handle reverse battery connections and brief +50/-50V transients too.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] Some Low-dropout regulator (LDO) alternatives, such as MCP1700 / MCP1711 / TPS7A05 / XC6206, have a very low quiescent current of less than 5 μA (approximately 1,000 times less than the LM78xx series) making them better suited for battery-powered devices.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] Common fixed voltages are 1.8 V, 2.5 V, 3.3 V (for low-voltage CMOS logic circuits), 5 V (for transistor-transistor logic circuits) and 12 V (for communications circuits and peripheral devices such as disk drives).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] In fixed voltage regulators the reference pin is tied to ground, whereas in variable regulators the reference pin is connected to the centre point of a fixed or variable voltage divider fed by the regulator's output.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/linear-regulator] A variable voltage divider such as a potentiometer allows the user to adjust the regulated voltage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] A **low-dropout regulator** (**LDO regulator**) is a type of a DC linear voltage regulator circuit that can operate even when the supply voltage is very close to the output voltage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] The disadvantage is that linear DC regulators must dissipate heat in order to operate.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] The adjustable low-dropout regulator debuted on April 12, 1977 in an *Electronic Design* article entitled "*Break Loose from Fixed IC Regulators*".
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] The article was written by Robert Dobkin, an IC designer then working for National Semiconductor.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] Because of this, National Semiconductor claims the title of "*LDO inventor*".
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] Dobkin later left National Semiconductor in 1981 and founded Linear Technology where he was the chief technology officer.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] The main components are a power FET and a differential amplifier (error amplifier).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] One input of the differential amplifier monitors the fraction of the output determined by the resistor ratio of R1 and R2.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] The second input to the differential amplifier is from a stable voltage reference (bandgap reference).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] If the output voltage rises too high relative to the reference voltage, the drive to the power FET changes to maintain a constant output voltage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] Low-dropout (LDO) regulators operate similarly to all linear voltage regulators.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] The main difference between LDO and non-LDO regulators is their schematic topology.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] Instead of an emitter follower topology, low-dropout regulators consist of an open collector or open drain topology, where the transistor may be easily driven into saturation with the voltages available to the regulator.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] This allows the voltage drop from the unregulated voltage to the regulated voltage to be as low as the saturation voltage across the transistor.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] When this voltage is less than Vref, the opamp will turn on the pass element.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] If a bipolar transistor is used, as opposed to a field-effect transistor or JFET, significant additional power may be lost to control it, whereas non-LDO regulators take that power from voltage drop itself.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] For high voltages under very low Vin-Vout difference there will be significant power loss in the control circuit.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] Because the power control element is an inverter, another inverting amplifier is required to control it, increasing circuit complexity compared to simple linear regulator.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] Power FETs may be preferable in order to reduce power consumption, yet this poses problems when the regulator is used for low input voltage, since FETs usually require 5 to 10 V to close completely.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] where $I_{\text{Q}}$ is the quiescent current required by the LDO for its internal circuitry.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] However, when the LDO is in full operation (i.e., supplying current to the load) generally: $I_{\text{OUT}}\gg I_{\text{Q}}$ .
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] It is important to keep thermal considerations in mind when using a low drop-out linear regulator.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] Having high current and/or a wide differential between input and output voltage could lead to large power dissipation.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] Additionally, efficiency will suffer as the differential widens.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] Depending on the package, excessive power dissipation could damage the LDO or cause it to go into thermal shutdown.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] Quiescent current is current drawn by the LDO in order to control its internal circuitry for proper operation.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] The series pass element, topologies, and ambient temperature are the primary contributors to quiescent current.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] Many applications do not require an LDO to be in full operation all of the time (i.e. supplying current to the load).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] In this idle state the LDO still draws a small amount of quiescent current in order to keep the internal circuitry ready in case a load is presented.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] In addition to regulating voltage, LDOs can also be used as filters.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] This is especially useful when a system is using switchers, which introduce a ripple in the output voltage occurring at the switching frequency.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] Left alone, this ripple has the potential to adversely affect the performance of oscillators, data converters, and RF systems being powered by the switcher.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] However, any power source, not just switchers, can contain AC elements that may be undesirable for design.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] Two specifications that should be considered when using an LDO as a filter are power supply rejection ratio (PSRR) and output noise.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] Speed is indicated by the rise time of the current at the output as it varies from 0 mA load current (no load) to the maximum load current.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] This is basically decided by the bandwidth of the error amplifier.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] It is also expected from an LDO to provide a quiet and stable output in all circumstances (example of possible perturbation could be: sudden change of the input voltage or output current).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] Stability analysis put in place some performance metrics to get such a behaviour and involve placing poles and zeros appropriately.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] Most of the time, there is a dominant pole that arise at low frequencies while other poles and zeros are pushed at high frequencies.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] PSRR refers to the LDO's ability to reject ripple it sees at its input.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] As part of its regulation, the error amplifier and bandgap reference attenuate any spikes in the input voltage that deviate from the internal reference to which it is compared.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] In an ideal LDO, the output voltage would be solely composed of the DC frequency.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] However, the error amplifier is limited in its ability to gain small spikes at high frequencies.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] As an example, an LDO that has a PSRR of 55 dB at 1 MHz attenuates a 1 mV input ripple at this frequency to just 1.78 μV at the output.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] A 6 dB increase in PSRR roughly equates to an increase in attenuation by a factor of 2.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] Most LDOs have relatively high PSRR at lower frequencies (10 Hz – 1 kHz).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] However, a Performance LDO is distinguished in having high PSRR over a broad frequency spectrum (10 Hz – 5 MHz).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] Having high PSRR over a wide band allows the LDO to reject high-frequency noise like that arising from a switcher.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] Similar to other specifications, PSRR fluctuates over frequency, temperature, current, output voltage, and the voltage differential.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] The noise from the LDO itself must also be considered in filter design.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] Like other electronic devices, LDOs are affected by thermal noise, bipolar shot noise, and flicker noise.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] Each of these phenomena contributes noise to the output voltage, mostly concentrated over the lower end of the frequency spectrum.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] In order to properly filter AC frequencies, an LDO must both reject ripple at the input while introducing minimal noise at the output.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] Efforts to attenuate ripple from the input voltage could be in vain if a noisy LDO just adds that noise back again at the output.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] Load regulation is a measure of the circuit's ability to maintain the specified output voltage under varying load conditions.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] The worst case of the output voltage variations occurs as the load current transitions from zero to its maximum rated value or vice versa.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] Line regulation is a measure of the circuit's ability to maintain the specified output voltage with varying input voltage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] Like load regulation, line regulation is a steady state parameter—all frequency components are neglected.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] Increasing DC open-loop current gain improves the line regulation.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] The transient response is the maximum allowable output voltage variation for a load current step change.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] Where ${\textstyle \Delta t_{1}}$ corresponds to the closed-loop bandwidth of an LDO regulator. ${\textstyle \Delta V_{\text{ESR}}}$ is the voltage variation resulting from the presence of the ESR ( ${\textstyle R_{\text{ESR}}}$ ) of the output capacitor.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/low-dropout-regulator] The application determines how low this value should be.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] A **switched-mode power supply** (**SMPS**), also called **switching-mode power supply**, **switch-mode power supply**, **switched power supply**, or simply **switcher**, is an electronic power supply that incorporates a switching regulator to convert electrical power efficiently.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Like other power supplies, a SMPS transfers power from a DC or AC source (often mains power, see AC adapter) to DC loads, such as a personal computer, while converting voltage and current characteristics.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Unlike a linear power supply, the pass transistor of a switching-mode supply continually switches between low-dissipation, full-on and full-off states, and spends very little time in the high-dissipation transitions, which minimizes wasted energy.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Voltage regulation is achieved by varying the ratio of on-to-off time (also known as duty cycle).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] In contrast, a linear power supply regulates the output voltage by continually dissipating power in the pass transistor.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] The switched-mode power supply's higher electrical efficiency is an important advantage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Switched-mode power supplies can also be substantially smaller and lighter than a linear supply because the transformer can be much smaller.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] This is because it operates at a high switching frequency which ranges from several hundred kHz to several MHz in contrast to the 50 or 60 Hz mains frequency used by the transformer in a linear power supply.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Despite the reduced transformer size, the power supply topology and electromagnetic compatibility requirements in commercial designs result in a usually much greater component count and corresponding circuit complexity.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Switching regulators are used as replacements for linear regulators when higher efficiency, smaller size or lighter weight is required.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] They are, however, more complicated; switching currents can cause electrical noise problems if not carefully suppressed, and simple designs may have a poor power factor.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] is a mechanically switched version of a flyback boost converter; the transformer is the ignition coil.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] On 23 June, British inventor Philip Ray Coursey applies for a patent in his country and United States, for his "Electrical Condenser".
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Electromechanical relays are used to stabilize the voltage output of generators.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] (1966–1972), incorporated early switched-mode power supplies.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] One of its applications is as a switched-mode regulator.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] starts using high-efficiency power supplies in its 7000-series oscilloscopes produced from about 1970 to 1995.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Robert Boschert develops simpler, low-cost switched-mode power supply circuits.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] By 1977, Boschert Inc. had grown to a 650-person company.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Robert Mammano, a co-founder of Silicon General Semiconductors, develops the first integrated circuit for SMPS control, model SG1524.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] is designed with a switched-mode power supply.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] was designed with a switched-mode power supply.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] A linear power supply (non-SMPS) uses a linear regulator to provide the desired output voltage by dissipating power in ohmic losses (e.g., in a resistor or in the collector–emitter region of a pass transistor in its active mode).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] A linear regulator regulates either output voltage or current by dissipating the electric power in the form of heat, and hence its maximum power efficiency is voltage-out divided by voltage-in since the voltage difference between input and output is wasted.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] In contrast, a SMPS changes output voltage and current by switching ideally lossless storage elements, such as inductors and capacitors, between different electrical configurations.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] In reality, these ideal components do not exist, so a switching power supply cannot be 100% efficient, but still provides a significant improvement in efficiency over a linear regulator.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Different switching configurations are used in SMPS designs.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] A boost converter acts like a step-up transformer for DC signals.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] A buck–boost converter works in a similar manner, but yields an output voltage which is opposite in polarity to the input voltage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Other buck circuits exist to boost the average output current with a reduction of voltage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] The main advantage of the switching power supply is greater efficiency (up to ~98–99%) and associated lower heat generation than linear regulators because the switching transistor dissipates little power when acting as a switch.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Other advantages include smaller size and lighter weight from the elimination of heavy and expensive line-frequency transformers.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Standby power loss is often also reduced with the elimination of these transformers.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Disadvantages include greater complexity, the generation of high-amplitude, high-frequency energy that the low-pass filter must block to avoid electromagnetic interference (EMI), a ripple voltage at the switching frequency and its harmonic frequencies.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Very low-cost SMPSs may couple electrical switching noise back onto the mains power line, causing interference with devices connected to the same AC circuit, such as audio equipment.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Non-power-factor-corrected SMPSs also cause harmonic distortion.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] There are two main types of regulated power supplies available: SMPS and linear.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] If the SMPS has an AC input, then the first stage is to convert the input to DC.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] An SMPS with a DC input does not require this stage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] In some power supplies (mostly computer ATX power supplies), the rectifier circuit can be configured as a voltage doubler by the addition of a switch operated either manually or automatically.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] This feature permits operation from power sources that are normally at 115 VAC or at 230 VAC.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] The rectifier produces an unregulated DC voltage, which is then sent to a large filter capacitor.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] The current drawn from the mains supply by this rectifier circuit occurs in short pulses around the AC voltage peaks.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] These pulses have significant high frequency energy, which reduces the power factor.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] To correct for this, many newer SMPS will use a special power factor correction (PFC) circuit to make the input current follow the sinusoidal shape of the AC input voltage, correcting the power factor.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Power supplies that use active PFC usually are auto-ranging, supporting input voltages from 90–264 VAC, with no input voltage selector switch.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] An SMPS designed for AC input can usually be run from a DC supply, because the DC would pass through the rectifier unchanged.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] If the power supply is designed for 115 VAC and has no voltage selector switch, the required DC voltage would be 163 VDC (115 × √2).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] This type of use may be harmful to the rectifier stage, however, as it will only use half of diodes in the rectifier for the full load.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] This could possibly result in overheating of these components, causing them to fail prematurely.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] On the other hand, if the power supply has a voltage selector switch, based on the Delon circuit, for 115/230 V (computer ATX power supplies typically are in this category), the selector switch would have to be put in the 230 V position, and the required voltage would be 325 VDC (230 × √2).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] The diodes in this type of power supply will handle the DC current just fine because they are rated to handle double the nominal input current when operated in the 115 V mode, due to the operation of the voltage doubler.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] This is because the doubler, when in operation, uses only half of the bridge rectifier and runs twice as much current through it.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] The inverter stage converts DC, whether directly from the input or from the rectifier stage described above, to AC by running it through a power oscillator, whose output transformer is very small with few windings, at a frequency of tens or hundreds of kilohertz.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] The frequency is usually chosen to be above 20 kHz, to make it inaudible to humans.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] The switching is implemented as a multistage (to achieve high gain) MOSFET amplifier.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] MOSFETs are a type of transistor with a low on-resistance and a high current-handling capacity.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] If the output is required to be isolated from the input, as is usually the case in mains power supplies, the inverted AC is used to drive the primary winding of a high-frequency transformer.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] This converts the voltage up or down to the required output level on its secondary winding.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] The output transformer in the block diagram serves this purpose.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] If a DC output is required, the AC output from the transformer is rectified.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] For output voltages above ten volts or so, ordinary silicon diodes are commonly used.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] For lower voltages, Schottky diodes are commonly used as the rectifier elements; they have the advantages of faster recovery times than silicon diodes (allowing low-loss operation at higher frequencies) and a lower voltage drop when conducting.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] For even lower output voltages, MOSFETs may be used as synchronous rectifiers; compared to Schottky diodes, these have even lower conducting state voltage drops.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] The rectified output is then smoothed by a filter consisting of inductors and capacitors.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] For higher switching frequencies, components with lower capacitance and inductance are needed.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Simpler, non-isolated power supplies contain an inductor instead of a transformer.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] This type includes *boost converters*, *buck converters*, and *buck–boost converters*.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] These belong to the simplest class of single input, single output converters which use one inductor and one active switch.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] The buck converter reduces the input voltage in direct proportion to the ratio of conductive time to the total switching period, called the duty cycle.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] For example, an ideal buck converter with a 10 V input operating at a 50% duty cycle will produce an average output voltage of 5 V.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] A feedback control loop is employed to regulate the output voltage by varying the duty cycle to compensate for variations in input voltage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] The output voltage of a boost converter is always greater than the input voltage and the buck–boost output voltage is inverted but can be greater than, equal to, or less than the magnitude of its input voltage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] There are many variations and extensions to this class of converters but these three form the basis of almost all isolated and non-isolated DC-to-DC converters.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] By adding a second inductor the Ćuk and SEPIC converters can be implemented, or, by adding additional active switches, various bridge converters can be realized.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Other types of SMPSs use a capacitor–diode voltage multiplier instead of inductors and transformers.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] These are mostly used for generating high voltages at low currents (*Cockcroft–Walton generator*).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] The low voltage variant is called charge pump.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] A feedback circuit monitors the output voltage and compares it with a reference voltage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Depending on design and safety requirements, the controller may contain an isolation mechanism (such as an opto-coupler) to isolate it from the DC output.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Switching supplies in computers, TVs and VCRs have these opto-couplers to tightly control the output voltage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] The feedback circuit needs power to run before it can generate power, so an additional non-switching power supply for stand-by is added.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Any switched-mode power supply that gets its power from an AC power line (called an "off-line" converter) requires a transformer for galvanic isolation.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Some DC-to-DC converters may also include a transformer, although isolation may not be critical in these cases.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] SMPS transformers run at high frequencies.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Most of the cost savings (and space savings) in off-line power supplies result from the smaller size of the high-frequency transformer compared to the 50/60 Hz transformers formerly used.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] The terminal voltage of a transformer is proportional to the product of the core area, magnetic flux, and frequency.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] By using a much higher frequency, the core area (and so the mass of the core) can be greatly reduced.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] However, core losses increase at higher frequencies.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Cores generally use ferrite material which has a low loss at the high frequencies and high flux densities used.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] The laminated iron cores of lower-frequency (<400 Hz) transformers would be unacceptably lossy at switching frequencies of a few kilohertz.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Also, more energy is lost during transitions of the switching semiconductor at higher frequencies.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Furthermore, more attention to the physical layout of the circuit board is required as parasitics become more significant, and the amount of electromagnetic interference will be more pronounced.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] At low frequencies (such as the line frequency of 50 or 60 Hz), designers can usually ignore the skin effect.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] For these frequencies, the skin effect is only significant when the conductors are large, more than 0.3 inches (7.6 mm) in diameter.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Switching power supplies must pay more attention to the skin effect because it is a source of power loss.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] At 500 kHz, the skin depth in copper is about 0.003 inches (0.076 mm) – a dimension smaller than the typical wires used in a power supply.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] The effective resistance of conductors increases, because current concentrates near the surface of the conductor and the inner portion carries less current than at low frequencies.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] The skin effect is exacerbated by the harmonics present in the high-speed pulse-width modulation (PWM) switching waveforms.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] The appropriate skin depth is not just the depth at the fundamental, but also the skin depths at the harmonics.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] In addition to the skin effect, there is also a proximity effect, which is another source of power loss.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Simple off-line switched-mode power supplies incorporate a simple full-wave rectifier connected to a large energy-storing capacitor.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Such SMPSs draw current from the AC line in short pulses when the mains instantaneous voltage exceeds the voltage across this capacitor.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] During the remaining portion of the AC cycle the capacitor provides energy to the power supply.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] As a result, the input current of such basic switched-mode power supplies has high harmonic content and relatively low power factor.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] This creates extra load on utility lines, increases heating of building wiring, the utility transformers, and standard AC electric motors, and may cause stability problems in some applications such as in emergency generator systems or aircraft generators.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Harmonics can be removed by filtering, but the filters are expensive.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Unlike displacement power factor created by linear inductive or capacitive loads, this distortion cannot be corrected by addition of a single linear component.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Additional circuits are required to counteract the effect of the brief current pulses.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Putting a current regulated boost chopper stage after the off-line rectifier (to charge the storage capacitor) can correct the power factor, but increases the complexity and cost.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] In 2001, the European Union put into effect the standard IEC 61000-3-2 to set limits on the harmonics of the AC input current up to the 40th harmonic for equipment above 75 W.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] The standard defines four classes of equipment depending on its type and current waveform.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] The most rigorous limits (class D) are established for personal computers, computer monitors, and TV receivers.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] To comply with these requirements, modern switched-mode power supplies normally include an additional power factor correction (PFC) stage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Switched-mode power supplies can be classified according to the circuit topology.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] The most important distinction is between isolated converters and non-isolated ones.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Non-isolated converters are simplest, with the three basic types using a single inductor for energy storage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] In the voltage relation column, *D* is the duty cycle of the converter, and can vary from 0 to 1.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] The input voltage (V1) is assumed to be greater than zero; if it is negative, for consistency, negate the output voltage (V2).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] When equipment is human-accessible, voltage limits of ≤ 30 V (r.m.s.) AC or ≤ 42.4 V peak or ≤ 60 V DC and power limits of 250 VA apply for safety certification (UL, CSA, VDE approval).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] The buck, boost, and buck–boost topologies are all strongly related.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Input, output and ground come together at one point.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] One of the three passes through an inductor on the way, while the other two pass through switches.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] One of the two switches must be active (e.g., a transistor), while the other can be a diode.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Sometimes, the topology can be changed simply by re-labeling the connections.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] A 12 V input, 5 V output buck converter can be converted to a 7 V input, −5 V output buck–boost by grounding the *output* and taking the output from the *ground* pin.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Likewise, SEPIC and Zeta converters are both minor rearrangements of the Ćuk converter.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] The neutral point clamped (NPC) topology is used in power supplies and active filters and is mentioned here for completeness.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Switchers become less efficient as duty cycles become extremely short.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] For large voltage changes, a transformer (isolated) topology may be better.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] All isolated topologies include a transformer, and thus can produce an output of higher or lower voltage than the input by adjusting the turns ratio.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] For some topologies, multiple windings can be placed on the transformer to produce multiple output voltages.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Some converters use the transformer for energy storage, while others use a separate inductor.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] By switching when a valley is detected, rather than at a fixed frequency, introduces a natural frequency jitter that spreads the RF emissions spectrum and reduces overall EMI.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Higher input voltage and synchronous rectification mode makes the conversion process more efficient.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] The power consumption of the controller also has to be taken into account.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Higher switching frequency allows component sizes to be shrunk, but can produce more RFI.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] A resonant forward converter produces the lowest EMI of any SMPS approach because it uses a soft-switching resonant waveform compared with conventional hard switching.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] For every 10-15 °C beyond 25 °C, failure rate doubles.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Most failures can be attributed to improper design and poor component selections.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Power supplies with capacitors that have reached the end of their life or suffer from manufacturing defects such as the capacitor plague will fail eventually.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] When either the capacitance decreases or the ESR increases, the regulator compensates by increasing the switching frequency, thereby subjecting the switching semiconductors to ever greater thermal stress.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Eventually the switching semiconductors fail, usually in a conductive manner.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] For power supplies without fail-safe protection, this may subject connected loads to the full input voltage and current, and wild oscillations can occur in the output.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Failure of the switching transistor is common.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Due to the large switching voltages this transistor must handle (around 325 V for a 230 VAC non-power-factor-corrected mains supply, otherwise usually around 390 V), these transistors often short out, in turn immediately blowing the main internal power fuse.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Power supplies in consumer products are frequently damaged by lightning strikes on power lines as well as internal short circuits caused by insects attracted to the heat and electrostatic fields.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Those events may damage any part of the power supply.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] The main filter capacitor will often store up to 325 volts long after the input power has been disconnected.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Not all power supplies contain a small "bleeder" resistor which slowly discharges the capacitor.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Contact with this capacitor can result in a severe electrical shock.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] The primary and secondary sides may be connected with a capacitor to reduce EMI and compensate for various capacitive couplings in the converter circuit, where the transformer is one.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] This may result in electric shock in some cases.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] The current flowing from line or neutral through a 2 kΩ resistor to any accessible part must, according to IEC 60950, be less than 250 μA for IT equipment.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Switched-mode power supply units (PSUs) in domestic products such as personal computers often have universal inputs, meaning that they can accept power from mains supplies throughout the world, although a manual voltage range switch may be required.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Switch-mode power supplies can tolerate a wide range of power frequencies and voltages.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Due to their high volumes of production, mobile phone chargers have always been particularly cost-sensitive.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] The first chargers were linear power supplies, but they quickly moved to the cost-effective ringing choke converter (RCC) SMPS topology, when new levels of efficiency were required.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] Switched-mode power supplies are used for DC-to-DC conversion as well.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] In heavy vehicles that use a nominal 24 VDC cranking supply, 12 V for accessories may be furnished through a DC/DC switch-mode supply.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] This has the advantage over tapping the battery at the 12 V position (using half the cells) that the entire 12 V load is evenly divided between all cells of the 24 V battery.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] In industrial settings such as telecommunications racks, bulk power may be distributed at a low DC voltage (e.g. from a battery backup system) and individual equipment items will have DC/DC switched-mode converters to supply required voltages.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] A common use for switched-mode power supplies is an extra-low-voltage source for lighting.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] For this application, they are often called "electronic transformers".
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] The term *switch mode* was widely used until Motorola claimed ownership of the trademark SWITCHMODE for products aimed at the switching-mode power supply market and started to enforce its trademark.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/switched-mode-power-supply] *Switching-mode power supply*, *switching power supply*, and *switching regulator* refer to this type of power supply.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] A **voltage regulator** is a system designed to automatically maintain a constant voltage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] It may use a simple feed-forward design or may include negative feedback.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] It may use an electromechanical mechanism or electronic components.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Depending on the design, it may be used to regulate one or more AC or DC voltages.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Electronic voltage regulators are found in devices such as computer power supplies, where they stabilize the DC voltages used by the processor and other elements.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] In automobile alternators and central power station generator plants, voltage regulators control the output of the plant.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] In an electric power distribution system, voltage regulators may be installed at a substation or along distribution lines so that all customers receive steady voltage independent of how much power is drawn from the line.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] A simple voltage regulator can be made from a resistor in series with a forward-biased diode (or series of diodes), forming a voltage divider of sorts.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Due to the logarithmic shape of diode V-I curves, the voltage across the diode changes only slightly due to changes in current drawn or changes in the input.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] When precise voltage control and efficiency are not important, this design may be adequate.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Since the forward voltage of a diode is small, this kind of voltage regulator is only suitable for low-voltage regulated output.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] When higher-voltage output is needed, a reverse-biased zener diode or a series of zener diodes may be employed.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Zener diode regulators make use of the zener diode's fixed reverse voltage, which can be quite large.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Feedback voltage regulators operate by comparing the actual output voltage to some fixed reference voltage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Any difference is amplified and used to control the regulation element in such a way as to reduce the voltage error.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] This forms a negative feedback control loop; increasing the open-loop gain tends to increase regulation accuracy but reduce stability.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Stability is the avoidance of oscillation, or ringing, during step changes in load or input voltage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] There will also be a trade-off between stability and the speed of the response to changes.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] However, many regulators have over-current protection, so that they will entirely stop sourcing current (or limit the current in some way) if the output current is too high, and some regulators may also shut down if the input voltage is outside a given range (see also: Crowbar (circuit)).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] In electromechanical regulators, voltage regulation is easily accomplished by coiling the sensing wire to make an electromagnet.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] The magnetic field produced by the current attracts a moving ferrous core held back under spring tension or gravitational pull.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] As voltage increases, so does the current, strengthening the magnetic field produced by the coil and pulling the core towards the field.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] The magnet is physically connected to a mechanical power switch, which opens as the magnet moves into the field.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] As voltage decreases, so does the current, releasing spring tension or the weight of the core and causing it to retract.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] This closes the switch and allows the power to flow once more.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] The relay(s) modulated the width of a current pulse to regulate the voltage output of the generator by controlling the average field current in the rotating machine which determines strength of the magnetic field produced which determines the unloaded output voltage per rpm.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Capacitors are not used to smooth the pulsed voltage as described earlier.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] The large inductance of the field coil stores the energy delivered to the magnetic field in an iron core so the pulsed field current does not result in as strongly pulsed a field.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Both types of rotating machine produce a rotating magnetic field that induces an alternating current in the coils in the stator.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] A generator uses a mechanical commutator, graphite brushes running on copper segments, to convert the AC produced into DC by switching the external connections at the shaft angle when the voltage would reverse.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] An alternator accomplishes the same goal using rectifiers that do not wear down and require replacement.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Modern designs now use *solid state* technology (transistors) to perform the same function that the relays perform in electromechanical regulators.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Electromechanical regulators are used for mains voltage stabilisation—see AC voltage stabilizers below.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Generators, as used in power stations, ship electrical power production, or standby power systems, will have automatic voltage regulators (AVR) to stabilize their voltages as the load on the generators changes.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] The first AVRs for generators were electromechanical systems, but a modern AVR uses solid-state devices.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] An AVR is a feedback control system that measures the output voltage of the generator, compares that output to a set point, and generates an error signal that is used to adjust the excitation of the generator.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] As the excitation current in the field winding of the generator increases, its terminal voltage will increase.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] The AVR will control current by using power electronic devices; generally a small part of the generator's output is used to provide current for the field winding.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Where a generator is connected in parallel with other sources such as an electrical transmission grid, changing the excitation has more of an effect on the reactive power produced by the generator than on its terminal voltage, which is mostly set by the connected power system.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Where multiple generators are connected in parallel, the AVR system will have circuits to ensure all generators operate at the same power factor.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] AVRs on grid-connected power station generators may have additional control features to help stabilize the electrical grid against upsets due to sudden load loss or faults.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] This is an older type of regulator used in the 1920s that uses the principle of a fixed-position field coil and a second field coil that can be rotated on an axis in parallel with the fixed coil, similar to a variocoupler.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] When the movable coil is positioned perpendicular to the fixed coil, the magnetic forces acting on the movable coil balance each other out and voltage output is unchanged.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Rotating the coil in one direction or the other away from the center position will increase or decrease voltage in the secondary movable coil.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] This type of regulator can be automated via a servo control mechanism to advance the movable coil position in order to provide voltage increase or decrease.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] A braking mechanism or high-ratio gearing is used to hold the rotating coil in place against the powerful magnetic forces acting on the moving coil.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Electromechanical regulators called *voltage stabilizers* or *tap-changers*, have also been used to regulate the voltage on AC power distribution lines.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] These regulators operate by using a servomechanism to select the appropriate tap on an autotransformer with multiple taps, or by moving the wiper on a continuously variable auto transfomer.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] If the output voltage is not in the acceptable range, the servomechanism switches the tap, changing the turns ratio of the transformer, to move the secondary voltage into the acceptable region.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] The controls provide a dead band wherein the controller will not act, preventing the controller from constantly adjusting the voltage ("hunting") as it varies by an acceptably small amount.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] The **ferroresonant transformer**, **ferroresonant regulator** or **constant-voltage transformer** is a type of saturating transformer used as a voltage regulator.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] These transformers use a tank circuit composed of a high-voltage resonant winding and a capacitor to produce a nearly constant average output voltage with a varying input current or varying load.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] The circuit has a primary on one side of a magnet shunt and the tuned circuit coil and secondary on the other side.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Voltage regulation results from magnetic saturation in the portion of the core associated with the resonant winding and secondary.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] The ferroresonant approach is attractive due to its lack of active components, relying on the square-loop magnetic characteristics of the core operating in saturation to absorb variations in average input voltage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Saturating transformers provide a simple rugged method to stabilize an AC power supply.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Older designs produced outputs with significant harmonic content.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Modern designs improve waveform quality, but the output is not an ideal sine wave.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] The ferroresonant action is a flux limiter rather than a voltage regulator, but with a fixed supply frequency it can maintain an almost constant average output voltage even as the input voltage varies widely.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] The ferroresonant transformers, which are also known as *constant-voltage transformers* (CVTs) or "ferros", are also good surge suppressors, as they provide high isolation and inherent short-circuit protection.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] A ferroresonant transformer can operate with an input voltage range ±40% or more of the nominal voltage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Output power factor remains in the range of 0.96 or higher from half to full load.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Because it regenerates an output voltage waveform, output distortion, which is typically less than 4%, is independent of any input voltage distortion, including notching.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Efficiency at full load is typically in the range of 89% to 93%.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] However, at low loads, efficiency can drop below 60%.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] The current-limiting capability also becomes a handicap when a CVT is used in an application with moderate to high inrush current, like motors, transformers or magnets.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] In this case, the CVT has to be sized to accommodate the peak current, thus forcing it to run at low loads and poor efficiency.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Minimum maintenance is required, as transformers and capacitors can be very reliable.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Some units have included redundant capacitors to allow several capacitors to fail between inspections without any noticeable effect on the device's performance.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Output voltage varies about 1.2% for every 1% change in supply frequency.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] For example, a 2 Hz change in generator frequency, which is very large, results in an output voltage change of only 4%, which has little effect for most loads.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] It accepts 100% single-phase switch-mode power-supply loading without any requirement for derating, including all neutral components.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Input current distortion remains less than 8% THD even when supplying nonlinear loads with more than 100% current THD.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Drawbacks of CVTs are their larger size, audible humming sound, and the high heat generation caused by saturation.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Some ferroresonant transformer have active control.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Voltage regulators or stabilizers are used to compensate for voltage fluctuations in mains power.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Large regulators may be permanently installed on distribution lines.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Small portable regulators may be plugged in between sensitive equipment and a wall outlet.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Automatic voltage regulators on generator sets to maintain a constant voltage for changes in load.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] The voltage regulator compensates for the change in load.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Power distribution voltage regulators normally operate on a range of voltages, for example 150–240 V or 90–280 V.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Many simple DC power supplies regulate the voltage using either series or shunt regulators, but most apply a voltage reference using a *shunt regulator* such as a Zener diode, avalanche breakdown diode, or voltage regulator tube.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] The power supply is designed to only supply a maximum amount of current that is within the safe operating capability of the shunt regulating device.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] If the stabilizer must provide more power, the shunt output is only used to provide the standard voltage reference for the electronic device, known as the voltage stabilizer.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] The voltage stabilizer is the electronic device, able to deliver much larger currents on demand.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Active regulators employ at least one active (amplifying) component such as a transistor or operational amplifier.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Shunt regulators are often (but not always) passive and simple, but always inefficient because they (essentially) dump the excess current which is not available to the load.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] When more power must be supplied, more sophisticated circuits are used.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] In the past, one or more vacuum tubes were commonly used as the variable resistance.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Modern designs like Shakti Servo use one or more transistors instead, perhaps within an integrated circuit.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Linear designs have the advantage of very "clean" output with little noise introduced into their DC output, but are most often much less efficient and unable to step-up or invert the input voltage like switched supplies.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] All linear regulators require a higher input than the output.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] If the input voltage approaches the desired output voltage, the regulator will "drop out".
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] The input to output voltage differential at which this occurs is known as the regulator's drop-out voltage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Low-dropout regulators (LDOs) allow an input voltage that can be much lower (i.e., they waste less energy than conventional linear regulators).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Entire linear regulators are available as integrated circuits.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] These chips come in either fixed or adjustable voltage types.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] A switching regulator works similar to an appliance charger.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] When battery charge is low, a charger is plugged in and energy is transferred to the battery.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] When charge is high, the charger disables itself, or is unplugged.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] A switching regulator nominally cycles hundreds to tens of thousands times per second automatically.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] The duty cycle is controlled by a similar feedback mechanism as in a linear regulator.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Because the series element is either fully conducting, or switched off, it dissipates almost no power; this is what gives the switching design its efficiency.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Switching regulators are also able to generate output voltages which are higher than the input, or of opposite polarity—something not possible with a linear design.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] In switched regulators, the pass transistor is used as a "controlled switch" and is operated at either cutoff or saturated state.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Hence the power transmitted across the pass device is in discrete pulses rather than a steady current flow.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Greater efficiency is achieved since the pass device is operated as a low-impedance switch.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] When the pass device is at cutoff, there is no current and it dissipates no power.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Again when the pass device is in saturation, a negligible voltage drop appears across it and thus dissipates only a small amount of average power, providing maximum current to the load.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] In either case, the power wasted in the pass device is very little and almost all the power is transmitted to the load.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Thus the efficiency of a switched-mode power supply is remarkably high – in the range of 70–90%.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Switched mode regulators rely on pulse-width modulation to control the average value of the output voltage.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] The average value of a repetitive-pulse waveform depends on the area under the waveform.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] When the duty cycle is varied, the average voltage changes proportionally.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Like linear regulators, nearly complete switching regulators are also available as integrated circuits (e.g.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Unlike linear regulators, these usually require an inductor for step-up or capacitor for step-down, that acts as the energy storage element.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] The IC regulators combine the reference voltage source, error op-amp, and pass transistor with short-circuit current limiting and thermal-overload protection.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Switching regulators are more prone to input noise, output noise, and instability than linear regulators.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] However, they provide much better power efficiency than linear regulators.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Regulators powered from AC power circuits can use silicon controlled rectifiers (SCRs) as the series device.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Whenever the output voltage is below the desired value, the SCR is triggered, allowing electricity to flow into the load until the AC mains voltage passes through zero (ending the half cycle).
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] SCR regulators have the advantages of being both very efficient and very simple, but because they can not terminate an ongoing half cycle of conduction, they are not capable of very accurate voltage regulation in response to rapidly changing loads.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] An alternative is the SCR shunt regulator which uses the regulator output as a trigger.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Both series and shunt designs are noisy, but powerful, as the device has a low on resistance.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Many power supplies use more than one regulating method in series.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] For example, the output from a switching regulator can be further regulated by a linear regulator.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] The switching regulator accepts a wide range of input voltages and efficiently generates a (somewhat noisy) voltage slightly above the ultimately desired output.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] That is followed by a linear regulator that generates exactly the desired voltage and eliminates nearly all the noise generated by the switching regulator.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Other designs may use an SCR regulator as the "pre-regulator", followed by another type of regulator.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] An efficient way of creating a variable-voltage, accurate output power supply is to combine a multi-tapped transformer with an adjustable linear post-regulator.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] A simple transistor regulator will provide a relatively constant output voltage *U*out for changes in the voltage *U*in of the power source and for changes in load *R*L, provided that *U*in exceeds *U*out by a sufficient margin and that the power handling capacity of the transistor is not exceeded.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] The output voltage of the stabilizer is equal to the Zener diode voltage minus the base–emitter voltage of the transistor, *U*Z − *U*BE, where *U*BE is usually about 0.7 V for a silicon transistor, depending on the load current.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] In this case, the operational amplifier drives the transistor with more current if the voltage at its inverting input drops below the output of the voltage reference at the non-inverting input.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] Using the voltage divider (R1, R2 and R3) allows choice of the arbitrary output voltage between Uz and Uin.
[src:voltage-regulators-deep/voltage-regulator] The output voltage can only be held constant within specified limits.
